    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Is it far/near from here?",
          "arabic": "هل هي بعيدة/قريبة من هنا؟"
        },
        "text": "To confirm the distance after getting directions, you can ask 'هي بعيدة/قريبة من هنا؟' (heyya ba'eeda/'areeba men hena?). Note the feminine forms 'بعيدة' and 'قريبة' because 'المسافة' (the distance) is feminine, or generally referring to the place's nature.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "هي بعيدة من هنا؟",
            "english": "Is it far from here?",
            "transliteration": "Heyya ba'eeda men hena?"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "هي قريبة من هنا؟",
            "english": "Is it close from here?",
            "transliteration": "Heyya 'areeba men hena?"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Thanking Someone",
          "arabic": "شكر شخص ما"
        },
        "text": "After receiving help, it's essential to thank the person. 'شكراً' (shokran) is universally understood. You can also use 'متشكر' (metshakker) for a male or 'متشكرة' (metshakkera) for a female, which means 'I am thankful'.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "شكراً جزيلاً.",
            "english": "Thank you very much.",
            "transliteration": "Shokran gazeelan."
          },
          {
            "arabic": "متشكر يا أستاذ.",
            "english": "I'm thankful, sir. (male speaker)",
            "transliteration": "Metshakker ya ostaz."
          },
          {
            "arabic": "متشكرة يا مدام.",
            "english": "I'm thankful, madam. (female speaker)",
            "transliteration": "Metshakkera ya madam."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "You're Welcome",
          "arabic": "على الرحب والسعة"
        },
        "text": "When someone thanks you, a common reply is 'العفو' (el 'afw) which means 'You're welcome' or 'Don't mention it'. Another friendly reply is 'مفيش شكر بينّا' (mafeesh shokr benna) meaning 'There's no need for thanks between us'.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "العفو.",
            "english": "You're welcome.",
            "transliteration": "El 'afw."
          },
          {
            "arabic": "مفيش شكر بينّا.",
            "english": "Don't mention it (lit. no thanks between us).",
            "transliteration": "Mafeesh shokr benna."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "practice-sentence",
      "sentence": {
